<subSubSection pageId="26" pageNumber="125" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="26.[136,1452,950,1949]" pageId="26" pageNumber="125">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,496,1598,1624]" pageId="26" pageNumber="125">Distribution and habitat:</emphasis>
—This species is widely distributed in the Neotropics, from eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1290,1400,1598,1624]" name="Colombia" pageId="26" pageNumber="125">Colombia</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[136,251,1634,1660]" name="Venezuela" pageId="26" pageNumber="125">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
to the eastern Andes and Atlantic coast of 
<collectingCountry box="[720,788,1634,1660]" name="Brazil" pageId="26" pageNumber="125">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Oliveira, I. L. C. &amp; Matos, A. O. &amp; Silva, C. &amp; Carvalho, M. L. S. &amp; Tyrrell, C. D. &amp; Clark, L. G. &amp; Oliveira, R. P." box="[802,1037,1634,1660]" pageId="26" pageNumber="125" pagination="61 - 81" refId="ref25821" refString="Oliveira, I. L. C., Matos, A. O., Silva, C., Carvalho, M. L. S., Tyrrell, C. D., Clark, L. G. &amp; Oliveira, R. P. (2020 a) Delving deeper into the phylogenetics of the herbaceous bamboos (Poaceae, Bambusoideae, Olyreae): evaluation of generic boundaries within the Parodiolyra / Raddiella clade uncovers a new genus. Botanical Journal of the Linnean Society 192: 61 - 81. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / botlinnean / boz 049" type="journal article" year="2020">
Oliveira 
<emphasis box="[902,957,1634,1660]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="125">et al.</emphasis>
2020a
</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry box="[1083,1154,1634,1660]" name="Brazil" pageId="26" pageNumber="125">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, it is registered in all states (Oliveira &amp; Oliveira 2020). It grows in the interior and along the edges of forests (
<bibRefCitation author="Oliveira, I. L. C. &amp; Matos, A. O. &amp; Silva, C. &amp; Carvalho, M. L. S. &amp; Tyrrell, C. D. &amp; Clark, L. G. &amp; Oliveira, R. P." box="[1063,1302,1670,1696]" pageId="26" pageNumber="125" pagination="61 - 81" refId="ref25821" refString="Oliveira, I. L. C., Matos, A. O., Silva, C., Carvalho, M. L. S., Tyrrell, C. D., Clark, L. G. &amp; Oliveira, R. P. (2020 a) Delving deeper into the phylogenetics of the herbaceous bamboos (Poaceae, Bambusoideae, Olyreae): evaluation of generic boundaries within the Parodiolyra / Raddiella clade uncovers a new genus. Botanical Journal of the Linnean Society 192: 61 - 81. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / botlinnean / boz 049" type="journal article" year="2020">
Oliveira 
<emphasis box="[1164,1221,1670,1696]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="125">et al.</emphasis>
2020a
</bibRefCitation>
). In the Serra do Cachimbo, it was found in Open ombrophilous forest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="26" pageNumber="125" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="26.[136,1452,950,1949]" pageId="26" pageNumber="125">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,328,1742,1768]" pageId="26" pageNumber="125">Comments:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName box="[356,574,1742,1768]" class="Arachnida" family="Cryptogeobiidae" genus="Taquara" kingdom="Animalia" order="Opiliones" pageId="26" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="micrantha">
<emphasis box="[356,574,1742,1768]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="125">Taquara micrantha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Soderstrom &amp; Zuloaga" authorityYear="1989" baseAuthorityName="Pilger 1930:" baseAuthorityYear="1049" box="[632,802,1742,1768]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Parodiolyra" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="26" pageNumber="125" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="luetzelburgii">
<emphasis box="[632,802,1742,1768]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="125">P. luetzelburgii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
share the paniculate synflorescence with lower branches whorled and bearing only male spikelets, but the former can be differentiated by its oblong-lanceolate leaves, glabrous on both surfaces and margins short-ciliate (vs. ovate-lanceolate leaves, densely scabrous to hispid on both surfaces and margins long-ciliate) and synflorescence with both male and female spikelets aristate (vs. only the female spikelet aristate), the male spikelet scabrous (vs. hispid) and the female anthecium foveolate (with small pits) over the entire surface (vs. only at the apex).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
